00:01:46.820 --> 00:01:49.830
&gt;&gt;Rachel: Thank you very much. All right,
so it's been a great pleasure for me to be

00:01:49.830 --> 00:01:50.830
here in New York today. Particularly as I
had to walk 40 blocks in the rain--

00:01:50.830 --> 00:01:51.830
[laughter]

00:01:51.830 --> 00:02:00.109
and realized after about block ten, that New
York drain engineers don't appear to know

00:02:00.109 --> 00:02:07.729
how to build drains. Secondly, that made me
realize, also, that architecture really is

00:02:07.729 --> 00:02:13.180
about dryness and that no matter what city
that you're in, rain is always a surprise.

00:02:13.180 --> 00:02:17.250
Which leads me, actually, to the materials
that I'm working with cause actually, they

00:02:17.250 --> 00:02:24.209
are designed to work with wetness. And I don't
know if anybody has managed to go around the

00:02:24.209 --> 00:02:28.250
exhibition just now. I haven't had a chance
to look so I can't tell you exactly where

00:02:28.250 --> 00:02:33.540
it is, but my contribution here are some black
and white films, which I did with Michael

00:02:33.540 --> 00:02:41.189
Simon Toon. And essentially, they are synthetic
agents made from simple oil and water, but

00:02:41.189 --> 00:02:47.330
have life-like properties. And so, the talk
I'm gonna do now really relates to why I'm

00:02:47.330 --> 00:02:54.890
interested in life as a technology and how
that is applied in a design and specifically

00:02:54.890 --> 00:02:59.670
architectural context. The examples I'm going
to use is a work that I've been doing around

00:02:59.670 --> 00:03:06.370
the city events, which, as you know, is rather
an interesting and tempestuous relationship

00:03:06.370 --> 00:03:16.270
with water. So essentially, I'm designing
living materials for the built environment.

00:03:16.270 --> 00:03:21.989
I'm gonna start with a quote, written in 1771,
that starts, "According to Mr. Blainville,

00:03:21.989 --> 00:03:27.239
who usually is trustworthy, one can predict
that in less than a hundred years will Venice

00:03:27.239 --> 00:03:33.099
be totally united with the rest of Italy and
you can walk dry-shod from Italy to the city."

00:03:33.099 --> 00:03:46.209
What we're really bad at is predicting the
future and what we're really good at is somehow,

00:03:46.209 --> 00:03:53.030
surviving it. According to scientists, life
was extinguished many times on early Earth,

00:03:53.030 --> 00:04:02.120
before it finally established itself 4.5 billion
years ago. The Earth's environment is not

00:04:02.120 --> 00:04:12.170
kind and for any structure on its surface
to persist requires a huge amount of energy.

00:04:12.170 --> 00:04:22.370
In nature, even mountains are moved. So, what
makes life so resilient? Well, the answer

00:04:22.370 --> 00:04:33.160
is we don't exactly know, but it's embodied,
it's robust, it's flexible and it's able to

00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:40.210
change with environmental fluctuations so
that it keeps its contingency at every moment

00:04:40.210 --> 00:04:49.130
because when it doesn't, it no longer possesses
that special quality of life. Life has this

00:04:49.130 --> 00:04:57.560
ability to persist, which is unlike any other
persistent structure on the Earth's surface.

00:04:57.560 --> 00:05:04.759
For example, the City of Venice, and I know
I'm personifying madly here, but this is to

00:05:04.759 --> 00:05:10.289
get my point across. For Venice to persist
against the forces of nature, the environment,

00:05:10.289 --> 00:05:17.150
the change in climate, it's standing there
in opposition to all this and it's had to

00:05:17.150 --> 00:05:24.009
ally itself with the contemporary technologies
of the time, not because of its living properties.

00:05:24.009 --> 00:05:30.400
So, Venice, when it was first established
as a city-state between the 12th, I'm sorry,

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:37.139
the 9th and the 12th century, was dependant
on agrarian technologies. Essentially, this

00:05:37.139 --> 00:05:43.620
meant land drainage because of the resources
of the sea. And with the settlement and it

00:05:43.620 --> 00:05:52.060
needed the construction of canals for transport
and the use of woodpiles to shore up the foundations

00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:57.550
of the developing settlement. And these, of
course, form a large part of the city even

00:05:57.550 --> 00:06:04.199
today. Now, with the advent of industrial
technologies, great wealth and power came

00:06:04.199 --> 00:06:15.949
to Venice. And it came with a price. In order
for the Industrial Revolution to create opportunities

00:06:15.949 --> 00:06:23.860
for growth and proliferation and wealth creation
for the population of Venice, and also the

00:06:23.860 --> 00:06:32.130
surrounding countries with which Venice was
trading, required top down intensive energy

00:06:32.130 --> 00:06:42.090
expensive processes that gave atomic precision
control over matter. And that had huge environmental

00:06:42.090 --> 00:06:48.840
cost; one that Venice is still paying today.
This is an industrial park set just north

00:06:48.840 --> 00:06:57.250
of Venice on the mainland, called Marghera.
I sometimes work in the laboratory there in

00:06:57.250 --> 00:07:07.020
the rather tube shaped tower. It's situated
between an oil refinery and a ship building

00:07:07.020 --> 00:07:14.130
yard. So, when you leave the lab at night,
one is confronted with Tunis that are set

00:07:14.130 --> 00:07:20.319
alight with toxic gases and the impression
of buildings that are moving as these ocean

00:07:20.319 --> 00:07:28.860
liners are being assembled and constructed
on moving frameworks; it's very, very surreal.

00:07:28.860 --> 00:07:35.360
So then, is it any wonder that environmentalists
are protesting wildly about the proposition

00:07:35.360 --> 00:07:42.500
of the Moses Project. Here's some graffiti
on one of the walls on a house in Venice,

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:50.680
protesting about the Moses Gates, the 78 mechanical
gates that are set to be installed in the

00:07:50.680 --> 00:07:58.210
lagoon of Venice and rather like the Danish
king, Kanut, are there to drive back the tides,

00:07:58.210 --> 00:08:07.731
because the aqua alta, very much like the
shoreline environment, is not kind. As you

00:08:07.731 --> 00:08:13.220
walk around the city, you start to see the
damage that the sea water, and particularly

00:08:13.220 --> 00:08:19.930
the salt, ravages on the brickwork. You actually
start seeing the very material substances

00:08:19.930 --> 00:08:26.770
within the city of Venice, the very fabric
of being digested away by the giant stomach

00:08:26.770 --> 00:08:31.699
of the elements and the lagoon substances.
You can see effervescence here; quite liberally,

00:08:31.699 --> 00:08:39.360
it's like the icing that's been dusted over
the walls. You can also see how very much

00:08:39.360 --> 00:08:46.029
the marble and even the concrete that's been
stuffed in the holes in the brickwork is suffering

00:08:46.029 --> 00:08:54.250
as the city fabric tries to retain integrity
at this very destructive interface. And you

00:08:54.250 --> 00:08:59.261
see all kinds of architectural desperation
as you walk along the city. Here, you see

00:08:59.261 --> 00:09:07.640
lion-like claw marks in the fabric of the
marble. And you also see odd bits of concrete

00:09:07.640 --> 00:09:13.769
pasted in these holes that can take the fist,
the size of a fist, like someone's fired cannonballs

00:09:13.769 --> 00:09:20.970
into the brickwork. And you'll see them also
filled with rubble and sand and rubbish and

00:09:20.970 --> 00:09:29.290
even chewing gum. But there is hope. In the
oddest place, perhaps, in a public garden

00:09:29.290 --> 00:09:36.800
to the east of Venice, is an oak tree. No
ordinary oak tree, this is a very special

00:09:36.800 --> 00:09:44.240
oak tree. It's at the center of a very special
building, The Canadian Pavilion, which was

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:51.290
constructed by Enrico Peresutti. Now, the
oak tree is special because it stands right

00:09:51.290 --> 00:09:56.170
in the middle of this building, which is wrapped
around it, according to the shell of a nautilus,

00:09:56.170 --> 00:10:03.040
which is a mollusk, a squid-like mollusk that
has this banded structure. And under the natural

00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:10.240
canopy is another canopy, an artificial canopy,
a cybernetic canopy, constructed by architect

00:10:10.240 --> 00:10:16.031
Phillip Beasley with his collaborator, Rob
Gorbet. And the golden fruits that you see

00:10:16.031 --> 00:10:19.980
within that canopy are fruits of my own enterprise,
some special chemical fruits, which I'll talk

00:10:19.980 --> 00:10:29.810
to you about in a minute. But this is the
Hylozoic Ground Project. Essentially, it fills

00:10:29.810 --> 00:10:37.040
the entire building and this cybernetic forest
literally responds to fluctuations within

00:10:37.040 --> 00:10:43.860
the environment. The passage of air causes
the feather-like filters to flicker and shed

00:10:43.860 --> 00:10:50.070
showers of dust into the atmosphere so you
can actually visualize the passage of the

00:10:50.070 --> 00:10:56.089
air movement through the gallery space. Those
long tube-like structures in the center of

00:10:56.089 --> 00:11:04.440
the gallery are actually swallowing tubes.
And what they do is they extend and contract

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:10.399
with hydraulics that are connected to the
cybernetic sensory systems, distributed throughout

00:11:10.399 --> 00:11:14.720
this forest of senses and affecters. Also,
under investigation, of course, is the presence

00:11:14.720 --> 00:11:21.790
of people and these swallowing tubes actually
are fitted with hairy tongues and you approach

00:11:21.790 --> 00:11:26.270
them, the senses detect your presence and
they raise their hairy tongue-like structures

00:11:26.270 --> 00:11:32.519
up to lick and tickle you. There were also
artificial crickets, which are those grape-like

00:11:32.519 --> 00:11:38.541
structures which are just to one side, above
the light structure that you can see to the

00:11:38.541 --> 00:11:45.860
left of the swallowing tubes. And they actually
scratch against each other and they make this

00:11:45.860 --> 00:11:55.370
sound that's a bit like a cicada. So, in this
rich, synthetic ecology, are the fruits. Now,

00:11:55.370 --> 00:11:59.930
this is one type of fruit. There are many
types of fruit and this one is a self-evolving

00:11:59.930 --> 00:12:08.460
chemistry based on the properties of inorganic
substances, impregnated into a gel-like matrix.

00:12:08.460 --> 00:12:15.250
And this is called the Liesegang reaction.
It's a precipitation diffusion reaction, which

00:12:15.250 --> 00:12:23.339
is a load of jargon, but essentially what
it is; it's an embodied form of fractal reductions.

00:12:23.339 --> 00:12:31.630
These chemistries gradually distribute themselves
through space and time and form a very elaborate

00:12:31.630 --> 00:12:37.440
pattern structures that have been driven by
the forces of gravity and fueled by their

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:44.020
chemical interactions in which they're contextualized.
But this is the particular fruit that I want

00:12:44.020 --> 00:12:49.889
you to have a look at. As you can see, there's
some opacities within its structure. And of

00:12:49.889 --> 00:12:55.540
course this is all fueled by the, and speeded
up by the LEDs that are placed underneath,

00:12:55.540 --> 00:13:02.480
under these fruits. And as we go closer, we
can actually see it's created of two layers

00:13:02.480 --> 00:13:09.020
of oil. Within them are cell-like structures
that are highly colored. In fact, those colors

00:13:09.020 --> 00:13:16.480
are there as indicators to show the public
that something is happening. And something's

00:13:16.480 --> 00:13:19.550
happening at a very, very, very slow rate,
because actually, I've have to slow this all

00:13:19.550 --> 00:13:25.300
down. Because believe it or not, and this
is one that's been shown by its reaction or

00:13:25.300 --> 00:13:31.579
its response to the LED, cause believe it
or not, this is actually a very rapid process.

00:13:31.579 --> 00:13:36.290
So, here is a film taken by my chemistry supervisor,
Martin Hanczyc, who actually invented this

00:13:36.290 --> 00:13:41.899
technology. It's called a dynamic oil and
water droplet system. What you're going to

00:13:41.899 --> 00:13:48.480
see is a qualitively new kind of technology
that's been called living technology. What's

00:13:48.480 --> 00:13:56.740
new about it is that it's inherently complex.
It is not controlled by push button technology.

00:13:56.740 --> 00:14:04.120
It does not respond according to the same
laws of operation that we've been accustomed

00:14:04.120 --> 00:14:10.360
to over the 19th and 20th century, with mechanical,
digital technologies. Essentially, this simple

00:14:10.360 --> 00:14:20.620
oil droplet in a medium of water, a little
bit of soap, and a lot of wriggling is a complete

00:14:20.620 --> 00:14:27.529
technology. You can't take, you can't break
it up into components. It exists as a whole

00:14:27.529 --> 00:14:34.360
from its essence; from the time of its birth.
What I find really amazing about this particular

00:14:34.360 --> 00:14:39.830
sequence is that for me, this is not only
technologically a birthing process, but I

00:14:39.830 --> 00:14:49.350
think also metaphorically it is heralding
a new age in computation. This is a form of

00:14:49.350 --> 00:14:56.500
material computation, in which the material
itself is actually able to make decisions

00:14:56.500 --> 00:15:02.660
and take actions depending on its environmental
context. So there are two ways of programming

00:15:02.660 --> 00:15:10.600
this agent. One can either program it according
to its environment, so it behaves in a life-like

00:15:10.600 --> 00:15:16.050
way. It can move around its environment, as
you can see here. It can sense it, so it can

00:15:16.050 --> 00:15:21.199
follow a great inter-, operates through a
primitive form of kinictaxis. It undergoes

00:15:21.199 --> 00:15:29.389
complex reactions, such as the shedding of
the skin, or even the production of a shell.

00:15:29.389 --> 00:15:33.199
Not only that, it likes other protocells,
so it doesn't just operate as a lone agent,

00:15:33.199 --> 00:15:38.279
but also in colonies. And in the video that
I've got installed here, you'll actually see

00:15:38.279 --> 00:15:44.190
some of these populations' scaled-like phenomena,
which actually have not been described using

00:15:44.190 --> 00:15:51.389
computational modeling. They are exhibiting,
in populations, phase-like phenomenon, so

00:15:51.389 --> 00:15:57.120
that it's almost like quorum sensing in bacteria,
if anybody knows what that is. It's essentially,

00:15:57.120 --> 00:16:01.620
bacteria operate according to their own little
set of rules and then when they're working

00:16:01.620 --> 00:16:04.709
in a population, they all start talking to
each other. And when there's a quorum present,

00:16:04.709 --> 00:16:10.230
whether it's six, whether it's eight, whether
its six thousand, suddenly there's a population

00:16:10.230 --> 00:16:15.540
scale signal that is passed amongst these
primitive bacteria, actually some them very

00:16:15.540 --> 00:16:22.550
sophisticated, too, and it causes a huge movement
of other bacteria towards this population.

00:16:22.550 --> 00:16:29.790
We just found something interesting, normally
food, and then it creates this mass scale

00:16:29.790 --> 00:16:34.060
migration towards the signaling center. So,
when these bacteria have reached the quorum,

00:16:34.060 --> 00:16:39.759
they're able to make a new product that they
don't make when they're less than a quorum.

00:16:39.759 --> 00:16:47.360
These protocells seem to be able to communicate
along those lines, even though they do not

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:52.850
possess any DNA. So, we can engineer them.
So we can either change their surroundings,

00:16:52.850 --> 00:16:59.180
so they can follow different traces in the
environment, or we can actually load up the

00:16:59.180 --> 00:17:04.940
body of the agents themselves with some chemical
information. And so, this is the final species

00:17:04.940 --> 00:17:11.680
of fruit that I've created. And this is one
that can take carbon dioxide out of solution,

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:17.560
which is dissolved both from the Venice water
in which this agent has been placed and also

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:22.300
in the respiratory gases it breathes out by
the gallery visitors. And what you're seeing

00:17:22.300 --> 00:17:27.930
is copper carbonate being dissolved in a halo-like
structure around the protocell that's worked

00:17:27.930 --> 00:17:34.690
its way down to the bottom of the pear-shaped
flask in which it's being housed. So, what

00:17:34.690 --> 00:17:38.800
could this be used for in an architectural
context? Well, I showed you some of the buildings

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:46.370
along the canal sites in Venice. Well, what
I've been able to do is to actually program

00:17:46.370 --> 00:17:54.210
oil droplets using this chemistry to actually
create shell-like structures, made of carbonate,

00:17:54.210 --> 00:17:59.620
which is like limestone, that bridge the gaps
between brick rubble. So, this is brick rubble

00:17:59.620 --> 00:18:05.890
that was collected from a walk around the
city, I've scooped it up, put it into a Petri

00:18:05.890 --> 00:18:11.460
dish, took it back to the lab, and then create
a paint-like substance, a watery paint. So,

00:18:11.460 --> 00:18:16.160
this material, unlike the architecture around
New York, which dumps all its water onto the

00:18:16.160 --> 00:18:21.570
street, wasting valuable resources, is actually
conducive to watery environments. So, you

00:18:21.570 --> 00:18:28.990
can actually start seeing that these blob-like
structures are starting to produce milky deposits

00:18:28.990 --> 00:18:35.720
as they repair the gaps between the brickwork,
but not only that, they actually create a

00:18:35.720 --> 00:18:40.430
shell around the brickwork itself, which is
fixing carbon dioxide and also producing a

00:18:40.430 --> 00:18:48.020
protective layer that delays, perhaps, the
corrosive effects of the highly saline and

00:18:48.020 --> 00:18:56.250
corrosive environment in which these buildings
are situated. And really, if you keep applying

00:18:56.250 --> 00:19:05.310
this, this paint, then you build up a form
of carbon dioxide capture an accretion around

00:19:05.310 --> 00:19:11.980
the wall substance itself. And so, literally,
with various paint applications, you can build

00:19:11.980 --> 00:19:18.170
this artificial shell-like structure around
the masonry. Within the next ten years, certainly

00:19:18.170 --> 00:19:25.450
maybe even within the next five, it is likely
that these agents will be able to reproduce.

00:19:25.450 --> 00:19:33.330
Currently, I've seen it done on an ad hoc
basis, so essentially, what DNA seems to do

00:19:33.330 --> 00:19:39.050
is to stack up the chances of cell division.
However, even without any DNA, these protocells

00:19:39.050 --> 00:19:48.670
actually divide and they fuse. It's a random
process. So, one can wonder whether or not

00:19:48.670 --> 00:19:54.620
this actually constitutes a form of synthetic
life, which is being created using a bottom

00:19:54.620 --> 00:20:00.980
up approach. So, it makes us wonder what it
is that we're thinking about when we're thinking

00:20:00.980 --> 00:20:06.510
about life-like processes. Technically though,
this is not a life and this remains a living

00:20:06.510 --> 00:20:13.400
technology. Really, really interestingly,
there are no more than about three or four

00:20:13.400 --> 00:20:20.200
chemicals being used in this particular substance
here. Its fat, water, a bit of surfactant,

00:20:20.200 --> 00:20:27.720
which like a soap just to break down the very
high pressures form surface tension around

00:20:27.720 --> 00:20:33.650
the oil droplet because of the reaction between
oil and water. Of course, oil has this schizophrenic

00:20:33.650 --> 00:20:42.280
relationship with water; it loves it on one
hand and hates it on the other hand. And any

00:20:42.280 --> 00:20:51.140
disturbance in populations of oil molecules,
in relationship to a water interface, causes

00:20:51.140 --> 00:20:59.801
great amount of movement and this actually
accounts for these physical phenomena that

00:20:59.801 --> 00:21:07.710
we see with these dynamic oil and water droplets.
So, what could we do with a system that's

00:21:07.710 --> 00:21:14.460
able to accrete a little bit of carbon dioxide?
And same, this is not geoengineering scale;

00:21:14.460 --> 00:21:21.420
literally this builds a crystalline layer
around it. And how could we use this in architectural,

00:21:21.420 --> 00:21:24.250
or even a design device? Well, propositionally,
we've come up with an idea that may provide

00:21:24.250 --> 00:21:28.010
a way that illustrates how living technology
is qualitively different to the industrial

00:21:28.010 --> 00:21:31.550
and digital technologies that we currently
know. So, in contrast to the Moses Gates,

00:21:31.550 --> 00:21:37.640
which propose to keep back the tide, what
we've decided was that the protocells could

00:21:37.640 --> 00:21:42.230
actually be released into the lagoon and programmed
to move away from the light-filled canals,

00:21:42.230 --> 00:21:49.310
where they'd make their way to the darkened
foundations of Venice, which, as you probably

00:21:49.310 --> 00:21:55.700
know, are built upon woodpiles. On reaching
this low energy threshold, they can then produce

00:21:55.700 --> 00:22:03.950
their carbonate and create these little synthetic
shells around the woodpiles and gradually,

00:22:03.950 --> 00:22:14.490
they accrete and form a reef-like structure
underneath the city. And so, the city of Venice

00:22:14.490 --> 00:22:18.880
is currently standing on soft delta soils
with stilettos. By creating a form of accretion

00:22:18.880 --> 00:22:24.510
underneath the city, we're changing those
stilettos into platform boots. And therefore,

00:22:24.510 --> 00:22:30.990
we're attenuating the gradual sinking of the
city of Venice into the soft delta soils.

00:22:30.990 --> 00:22:35.810
Obviously, Venice's problems and its relationship
with the environment is complex and certainly

00:22:35.810 --> 00:22:42.790
accretion and the spreading of the point load
of the city is not going to be enough to solve

00:22:42.790 --> 00:22:50.690
