01:24:02.800 --> 01:24:03.800
exist in some fashion. I think it's the kind
of narrative that we find in science fiction

01:24:03.800 --> 01:24:04.800
that we're actually in love with. Science
fiction used to be slightly pooh-poohed. I

01:24:04.800 --> 01:24:05.800
think if you'd mentioned that before, people
would get psyched or upset, but if you look

01:24:05.800 --> 01:24:06.800
at the history of science fiction, its contribution
to humanity is immense. You can go all the

01:24:06.800 --> 01:24:07.800
way back to Jules Verne, right? Hundreds of
years ago, he was, he wrote a narrative, not

01:24:07.800 --> 01:24:08.800
a promissory narrative, he didn't make any
promises, he just said, "Here's a narrative

01:24:08.800 --> 01:24:09.800
about getting to the moon." And he got into
the entire culture of how that would happen.

01:24:09.800 --> 01:24:10.800
And he imagined it would be a staged rocket
that would leave from Florida, that would

01:24:10.800 --> 01:24:11.800
drop off elements, land on the moon, return
with a different capsule that would go through

01:24:11.800 --> 01:24:12.800
the atmosphere and would land in the water.
And you can imagine a hundred years later,

01:24:12.800 --> 01:24:13.800
the engineers at NASA, directed by Kennedy
to go to the moon. They said, "Well, what

01:24:13.800 --> 01:24:14.800
are some ideas?" They probably read Jules
Verne and said, "Let's see if this works out."

01:24:14.800 --> 01:24:15.800
Did some numbers and started being more and
more convinced that that's the way to do it.

01:24:15.800 --> 01:24:27.460
I think that that's, it stays in our hearts
and our minds and our imagination. The more

01:24:27.460 --> 01:24:44.070
